\begin_layout Abstract
We revisit Tarski's Algebra of Relations (
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
),
 an old formalism of relations predating Codd's relational algebra by over 100 years,
 as a new foundation for relational databases.
 We argue 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 provides a better abstraction at both the semantic level and the physical level,
 with the advent of column stores and modern application code.
 To demonstrate the strengths of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
,
 we design and implement Prela,
 a compositional and controllable query language,
 and show that queries written in Prela are concise,
 clear,
 and efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the past 50 years,
 the relational model
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/cacm/Codd70"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has cemented its status as the foundation underlying database systems.
 The relational algebra has therefore become the central abstraction bridging high-level semantics to low-level execution.
 However,
 the world has changed both below and above this abstraction.
 At the system level,
 OLAP engines increasingly adopt column-oriented storage,
 while transactional systems are built upon a key-value core.
 On the application side,
 researchers are pushing towards higher abstractions like the Entity/Relationship model
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/cidr/Deshpande25,DBLP:journals/tods/Chen76"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 with the goal to better support nested and graph data,
 and to reconcile the long-standing impedance mismatch between relational schema and application code.
 As a result,
 both the physical layer and the semantic layer have drifted away from the original table-oriented abstraction.
 Yet,
 as we will show,
 the independent evolution of the physics and the semantics of relational data have lead to the same destiny!
 This reunion calls for new abstractions that better connect queries to their execution.
 In this paper,
 we revisit an old formalism of relations predating Codd's relational algebra by over 100 years.
 This formalism was developed by logicians from De Morgan,
 Peirce,
 Schröder,
 to Tarski and Givant,
 and is now commonly know as Tarski's Algebra of Relations (
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
)
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/jsyml/Tarski41,tarski1987formalization,Maddux1991-MADTOO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To demonstrate the potential of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 as a new foundation for modern database systems,
 we design and implement Prela,
 a 
\emph on
compositional
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
controllable
\emph default
 query language.
 Using Prela,
 the programmer can write concise,
 clear,
 and efficient queries,
 all the while retaining fine-grained control over low-level details of query execution.
 
\end_layout

