\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What goes around comes around
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite countless attempts at replacement,
 the relational model has stood the test of time
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stonebraker2005what,DBLP:journals/sigmod/StonebrakerP24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This paper does not try to supplant the relational model,
 but rather to refine and evolve it to meet modern needs.
 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
—
despite being a century older—
can be understood as an evolution of the relational algebra towards columns stores and modern application code;
 the Prela language can also be considered a prototype demonstrating how SQL can be extended and made more flexible.
 In particular,
 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 and Prela stand upon the two pillars of physical and logical independence:
 the relation-centric 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 assumes an abstract data model allowing for different physical implementations including dense vectors,
 hash maps,
 or bit sets;
 the corresponding Prela query accepts type annotations to specify any of these data structures.
 Queries can be declared as views and used as inputs to other queries,
 should the logical schema change;
 addition and deletion of orthogonal attributes and relationships also will not break existing queries.
 We believe ideas of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 and Prela can be incorporated into mainstream relational databases to simplify their design and implementation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
TAR
\noun on
 
\noun default
in theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection between Tarski and Codd has been noted as early as the first 
\noun on
PODS
\noun default
 conference in 1982,
 when Imielinski and Lipski
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1145/588111.588139,DBLP:journals/jcss/ImielinskiL84"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrated how to emulate Codd's relational algebra with Tarski's 
\emph on
cylindric algebras
\emph default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "henkin1971cylindric,henkin1985cylindric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 an extension of Boolean algebras related to 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
.
 Gyssens,
 Saxton and Van Gucht
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:books/mk/freytagMV91/GyssensSG91"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed an alternative approach to modeling relational algebra by enhancing 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 with certain 
\emph on
pairing/tagging
\emph default
 operations that introduce tuple values.
 Prela's product operation 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.and()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 fills a similar role to pairing and tagging,
 but is more natural for writing queries.
 Database theorists have also used 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 to analyze graph and tree query languages like Regular Path Queries,
 XPath,
 and SPARQL
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/icdt/FletcherGLBGVW11,DBLP:journals/jacm/LibkinMV16,DBLP:journals/igpl/SurinxFGLBGVW15,DBLP:journals/jlap/HellingsWGG22,DBLP:journals/lmcs/0001CMB24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is thanks to how 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
's main operator,
 the relational composition,
 conveniently models path traversal.
 Nevertheless,
 none of these languages were built upon 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
.
 Van den Bussche
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/csl/Bussche01"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 gives an introduction and survey of how Tarski's ideas have been applied to database theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\noun on
TAR 
\noun default
in practice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been sporadic efforts to bring the theory of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 into practice.
 In 1992,
 Paredaens et al.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/sigmod/ParedaensBAGGTGSS92"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presented 
\noun on
GOOD
\noun default
,
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Graph-Oriented Object Database
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 and envisioned an implementation over a data model based on 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
.
 The 
\noun on
GOOD
\noun default
 system itself,
 however,
 was built atop a standard relational engine.
 A follow-on technical report by Sarathy and Van Gucht
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sarathy1993implementation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes an implementation of the 
\noun on
GOOD
\noun default
 model in the 
\noun on
IUGQL
\noun default
 query language.
 More recently,
 Libkin et al.
 developed 
\noun on
TriAL
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:journals/tods/LibkinRSV18"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 a language for recursive queries over RDF data based on a 
\emph on
triple algebra
\emph default
 related to 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
.
 Compared to these languages,
 Prela focuses on traditional non-recursive queries over relational data.
 Prela also uses 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 directly both as the surface syntax and the underlying storage abstraction,
 whereas the aforementioned systems all come with a separate,
 declarative query syntax.
 This indirection complicates system design,
 obstructs performance tuning,
 and obscures the beauty of 
\noun on
TAR.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Dataframes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Libraries like 
\noun on
pandas
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mckinney2010pandas,pandas"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\noun on
polars
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "polars"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and 
\noun on
datafusion
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lamb2024datafusion"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\noun on
 
\noun default
provide an interface to tabular data based on relational algebra.
 As such,
 these libraries also struggle to express multi-table joins succinctly,
 as each join operation must specify the join condition explicitly.
 Moreover,
 since the libraries typically implement column names as attributes of each dataframe object,
 the user must take great care and rename columns when joining tables,
 to avoid conflicts and ambiguity.
 As a result,
 queries spanning multiple tables look even more complicated in dataframes code as compared to their SQL counterpart.
 At the engine level,
 
\noun on
pandas
\noun default
 executes queries as-is,
 albeit 
\emph on
eagerly
\emph default
 – every dataframe operation immediately produces a result when it is called.
 Other more optimized engines including 
\noun on
polars
\noun default
 and 
\noun on
datafusion
\noun default
 generate and optimize query plans,
 much like traditional OLAP databases.
 Prela's engine can be thought of as implementing a lazy,
 push-based execution model.
 Operators do not materialize intermediate results unless necessary,
 and the unoptimized queries already run fast.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
SQL extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The secret behind the longevity of SQL is its ability to absorb ideas proposed in new query languages.
 Recent work by Shute,
 Zheng,
 and Kudtarkar
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/cidr/ShuteZK26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed SQL extensions to better support semantic data modeling and graph workloads.
 Their proposal lead to several design points strikingly similar to those taken by Prela.
 For example,
 they also support implicit joins without specifying join conditions,
 as well as multi-hop join/access syntax similar to the last line of Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

.
 With Prela,
 we aim to demonstrate such extensions to SQL can be grounded on the firm theoretical foundation of 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
,
 and that they are not merely syntactic sugars,
 but can produce tangible performance benefits when connected to the underlying execution engine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Functional data models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several functional data models have been proposed over the years
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/sigmod/BunemanF79,DBLP:conf/sigmod/Shipman79,DBLP:conf/edbt/Beech88,Chan1987AdaDBMS,Gray2005FunctionalApproach,Gray2018AMOSQL,Gray2018FunctionalDataModel,Gray2018FunctionalQueryLanguage,DBLP:journals/cj/KulkarniA86"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and recent work by Dittrich
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:conf/edbt/Dittrich26"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 envisioned a data model and query language where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

everything is a function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 He then proposes a 
\emph on
function algebra
\emph default
 where the operators are higher-order functions consuming and producing functions.
 Prela can be considered a realization of that vision over 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
:
 a relation in 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 is precisely a (multi-valued) function.
 Prela also goes beyond the syntax and semantics of the query language itself and explores the synergy between high-level abstraction and low-level execution.
 
