\begin_layout Standard
Composition is powerful because it allows us to 
\emph on
zoom in
\emph default
 by composing multiple relations.
 This is what happened on the last line of Figure
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:JOB-query-16b"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.s()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is simply an alias for 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 and the expression 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast.s(person).s(alias).s(text)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which reads 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cast's person's alias's text
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 composes four binary relations in a chain:
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cast
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maps each movie to its cast,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
person
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maps each cast to its actors,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
alias
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maps the actors to their aliases,
 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
text
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maps the alias 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

object/entity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the string value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second most important operator is the 
\emph on
cross product
\emph default
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r.and(s)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which joins the relations on their first column,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r\bowtie_{r.1=s.1}s$
\end_inset

.
 Crucially,
 the output is still a 
\emph on
binary
\emph default
 relation,
 whose second column is a tuple containing one value each from the second column of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
r
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
s
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For example,
 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
title.and(year)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the relation mapping 0 to (The Godfather,
 1972),
 1 to (Seven Samurai,
 1954),
 and 2 to (Casablanca,
 1942).
 Combining with 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.select()
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 the Prela query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
movie.select(title.and(year).and(keyword))
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implements the SQL query 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT ID,
 title,
 year,
 keyword FROM movie
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the cross product was not part of Tarski's original algebra,
 but our own invention to serve a practical purpose in Prela,
 namely the need to output multiple columns.
 We only learned after-the-fact that there is also a theoretical justification for the product operator:
 the original 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
 was not expressive enough to capture all of Codd's relational algebra,
 and one approach to bridge this gap is to introduce the so-called 
\emph on
pairing operators
\emph default
 to 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default

\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DBLP:books/mk/freytagMV91/GyssensSG91"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It turns out our cross product can emulate these pairing operators,
 thereby offering another way to extend 
\noun on
TAR
\noun default
's expressive power.
 
\end_layout

